In re lycra - it sure beats having your pants jammed up your crack for hours on end :)

@Jay 
Ok, I can’t unsee that mental image now!


Do emus wear Lycra?

@Kirk House 

Yes, exactly.  I think under some circumstances, maybe a server glitch or something like that, the server doesn't realize the puzzle is complete. 

Removing and replacing a letter should do the trick.  If that *doesn't* work, then make sure you're aware of your recent changes (maybe take a screen shot) and then go out completely and come back in.  You might find some empty spaces (hence the screen shot), but when you fill them back in it should respond normally.

@Sam 

For *you* 90% of it required Wikipedia and Google searches.

I'm fairly certain that a good number of people got it without any help.

@Sam 

Ok, sorry.  

No offense intended.

@Mick 

I tend to agree with you.  

But I do think SP has something of a point, considering that *hearing* the song title and *reading* it are kinda two separate things.

@Steve L 

It's probably like a food order being "up." 

I'm pretty sure that there were at least three or four times when the puzzle itself hasn't dropped right at 10 in the last 12 months, and as you say, I busied myself accordingly, but I do get the sense that there's really no-one besides -- occasionally -- Deb on duty at 10 pm or on the weekends. Offensive comments are usually not removed until mid-morning the next day, for example, and sometimes will last through Sunday if they are posted Friday night or Saturday. My sense is that the IT people who are in charge of the games pages are M-F 9-5'ers.

@Steve L 

I bike but don’t follow the Tour de France. But my brother was enough of a fan that his widow had to discard a crate full of videotapes of the Tour that Kurt had saved from years past.

I also have some good friends who are devoted Tour watchers. Thought they also follow the Giro d’Italia and the Veulta a España, I don’t remember ever hearing the three races referred to as the Grand Tour.

@David Connell - I'm not sure a dictionary would be much help. 

Many complainers consider any word that is not in their own personal knowledge base to be "obscure" or "not really a word" even if it shows up in a dictionary -- or all dictionaries. 

How sad it must be to be so resistant to learning new words, especially for people who are solving crosswords.

@Eva H. 

Pretty sure I’ve never seen a crossword puzzle with no proper nouns, let alone one in the NYT.

But what do I know? 🤷‍♀️

@dutchiris this comment is exactly how I imagine smug crossword nuts patting themselves on the back when they know ridiculously obscure references in unenjoyable crossword puzzles. 

I'm glad you enjoyed it and I hope the lift it gave your ego serves you well. 

I thought it was a dreadful puzzle, though, and I don't have an ounce of regret for not having the slightest idea who these proper nouns are.

@Darren 

I don't get it.  NO ONE has ever heard of it, but EVERYONE can revel in their genius.

So, which is it?  No one?  Or Everyone?

@Vaer 
Whoops, this was meant as a Thursday comment.  Not sure how it wound up here. At least it's not a spoiler. 

Bad emus.

@Anita

I came looking for a bicycle pun, Anita.
I’m glad we SPOKE.

@Barry Ancona Me, et al. Vicious cycle is a somewhat common misstatement sort of like "irregardless".
Google vicious cycle (as of today) and it will auto-correct it to vicious circle.
It's not too out of line for this TDF themed puzzle to use the corrupted version, but since I didn't like this puzzle much anyway, I will not be giving it the benefit of the doubt.
